{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641819"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17906"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17906"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.47,0.06,0.06,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58260"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"10049"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOne hormone is produced by endocrine cells in the ileum and colon. It inhibits gastric emptying, gastric acid secretion, and pancreatic exocrine secretion. It acts via neuropeptide Y receptors on the dorsal vagal system and on gastric mucosal enterochromaffin cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormones has these characteristics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholecystokinin (CCK)","Peptide YY (PYY)","Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1)","Insulin","Ghrelin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptide YY (PYY)\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone produced by endocrine cells in the ileum and colon in response to a meal. It plays a role in reducing appetite and inhibiting gastric and pancreatic secretions. PYY acts on neuropeptide Y receptors, influencing the dorsal vagal system and gastric mucosal enterochromaffin cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystokinin (CCK)\u003C/strong\u003E is another hormone released in response to food intake, particularly fats and proteins, but it primarily stimulates the gallbladder to contract and the pancreas to secrete enzymes, rather than inhibiting gastric functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1)\u003C/strong\u003E is also released in response to food intake and enhances insulin secretion, but it does not primarily act via neuropeptide Y receptors or have the same inhibitory effects on gastric functions as PYY.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone produced by the pancreas in response to increased blood glucose levels, promoting glucose uptake by cells, but it does not have the described effects on gastric and pancreatic secretions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone that stimulates appetite and is released primarily from the stomach, having opposite effects to those described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peptide YY (PYY) is produced in response to a meal by endocrine cells in the ileum and colon.","PYY inhibits gastric emptying, gastric acid secretion, and pancreatic exocrine secretion.","PYY acts via neuropeptide Y (NPY) receptors on the dorsal vagal system and gastric mucosal enterochromaffin cells."],"references":[